a problem that they

00:07:54.260 --> 00:07:56.510
were trying to solve or
a quality or an attribute

00:07:56.510 --> 00:07:58.490
that they wanted to
put into the world.

00:07:58.490 --> 00:08:00.729
And the Tribeca Film
Festival was a story

00:08:00.729 --> 00:08:02.270
that I happened to
fall in love with.

00:08:02.270 --> 00:08:04.853
As I said, I grew up in Toronto,
and the Toronto Film Festival

00:08:04.853 --> 00:08:06.090
was a major event.

00:08:06.090 --> 00:08:09.410
And I was always curious to know
in a cluttered, cloudy field

00:08:09.410 --> 00:08:12.170
of Sundance, and
Cannes, and Toronto,

00:08:12.170 --> 00:08:15.620
how does a modern festival like
Tribeca pop up and succeed?

00:08:15.620 --> 00:08:17.960
To which the answer from
the founders of Tribeca,

00:08:17.960 --> 00:08:20.700
De Niro, and Rosenthal,
and Hatkoff was the world

00:08:20.700 --> 00:08:23.245
didn't actually need
another film festival.

00:08:23.245 --> 00:08:25.370
And so if all we were
creating was a film festival,

00:08:25.370 --> 00:08:26.487
this would have failed.

00:08:26.487 --> 00:08:28.820
And whereas the world didn't
need another film festival,

00:08:28.820 --> 00:08:31.040
the world didn't need the
Tribeca Film Festival.

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:33.679
And I'll share with you the
story they shared with me.

00:08:33.679 --> 00:08:35.720
The three of them grew up
in and around New York.

00:08:35.720 --> 00:08:37.309
They happened to love film.

00:08:37.309 --> 00:08:39.409
They were people
of means and people

00:08:39.409 --> 00:08:42.201
with tremendous influence,
who at one point

00:08:42.201 --> 00:08:43.909
toyed with the idea
of introducing a film

00:08:43.909 --> 00:08:45.920
festival into New
York because that

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:47.851
was their lifelong
passion, but they never

00:08:47.851 --> 00:08:49.850
really saw a hole in the
conventional landscape.

00:08:49.850 --> 00:08:51.900
It just didn't make sense.

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:53.630
And then 9/11 happened.

00:08:53.630 --> 00:08:56.570
And here you have some people
that weren't just filmmakers,

00:08:56.570 --> 00:08:59.270
but had a deep care
and consideration

00:08:59.270 --> 00:09:01.075
for the city that was home.

00:09:01.075 --> 00:09:02.450
And they observed
from where they

00:09:02.450 --> 00:09:04.900
sat, as people with
means and influence,

00:09:04.900 --> 00:09:07.250
that if people weren't
going out and patronizing

00:09:07.250 --> 00:09:10.400
the businesses that were still
around, that not only would New

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:14.370
York feel devoid of
life and vitality,

00:09:14.370 --> 00:09:17.840
but as commerce would dwindle,
the city would get worse, not

00:09:17.840 --> 00:09:19.020
better, over time.

00:09:19.020 --> 00:09:21.150
And so they went
out to restaurants.

00:09:21.150 --> 00:09:22.760
And they thought,
what if we can get

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:25.100
more of our friends, who also
have influence and means,

00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:26.090
to come with us?

00:09:26.090 --> 00:09:28.700
And they created a program
called Dinner Downtown.

00:09:28.700 --> 00:09:32.600
This existed before the Tribeca
Film Festival was ever born.

00:09:32.600 --> 00:09:35.314
And all they did was they
said, you, my friend, you

00:09:35.314 --> 00:09:36.230
should come to dinner.

00:09:36.230 --> 00:09:38.120
And you should invite
10 of your friends,

00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:40.290
and let's keep doing
the same thing.

00:09:40.290 --> 00:09:42.230
And so they grew
an event which they

00:09:42.230 --> 00:09:44.570
ran on more than one occasion,
where hundreds of people,

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:46.100
very influential
people, including

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:49.664
Bill Clinton and Queen Noor,
would come and patronize

00:09:49.664 --> 00:09:50.330
the restaurants.

00:09:50.330 --> 00:09:52.070
And what they
observed was if this

00:09:52.070 --> 00:09:54.770
is what we can do with
small application,

00:09:54.770 --> 00:09:56.930
could we somehow
scale that to impact

00:09:56.930 --> 00:09:58.340
more of the City of New York?

00:09:58.340 --> 00:10:00.290
They actually-- their
language was they

00:10:00.290 --> 00:10:02.150
thought about contribution
before they ever

00:10:02.150 --> 00:10:03.394
thought about extraction.

00:10:03.394 --> 00:10:05.060
And the contribution
they wanted to make

00:10:05.060 --> 00:10:08.240
was more people in New York,
coming out, patronizing,

00:10:08.240 --> 00:10:11.540
consuming, adding
vitality and culture.

00:10:11.540 --> 00:10:13.340
And they simply
used film, the thing

00:10:13.340 --> 00:10:17.210
they knew really well, as a
galvanizing mechanism to do it.

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:18.560
They made a lofty promise.

00:10:18.560 --> 00:10:20.450
It was close to
the end of the year

00:10:20.450 --> 00:10:23.720
and they basically said
four months into 2002,

00:10:23.720 --> 00:10:26.374
the Tribeca Film
Festival would be born.

00:10:26.374 --> 00:10:27.540
They lead with their hearts.

00:10:27.540 --> 00:10:28.820
They lead with their passion.

00:10:28.820 --> 00:10:30.920
They lead with their ambition.

00:10:30.920 --> 00:10:33.110
But they weren't
fully mature thinkers.

00:10:33.110 --> 00:10:35.450
They didn't actually think
it all the way through,

00:10:35.450 --> 00:10:37.976
in terms of how do we
get money for this thing?

00:10:37.976 --> 00:10:39.350
How do we communicate
this thing?

00:10:39.350 --> 00:10:41.725
How do we make sure that not
only our hundreds of friends

00:10:41.725 --> 00:10:44.660
know, but thousands of people
and more from around the world?

00:10:44.660 --> 00:10:46.550
And it wasn't until
very late in the game

