SPEAKER: Oh, it is?

00:38:05.850 --> 00:38:07.650
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:38:07.650 --> 00:38:11.284
I have like three questions,
but I'll ease into them

00:38:11.284 --> 00:38:12.575
and give other people a chance.

00:38:12.575 --> 00:38:16.140
It was a really
interesting talk.

00:38:16.140 --> 00:38:20.070
I'm wondering how much the
advancement of technology

00:38:20.070 --> 00:38:24.920
and the internet, and how
much that has made things

00:38:24.920 --> 00:38:28.940
move much more quickly,
has impacted maybe

00:38:28.940 --> 00:38:31.550
the newer brands that
are trying to establish

00:38:31.550 --> 00:38:37.010
in terms of their
ethics and their morals.

00:38:37.010 --> 00:38:40.000
Because if they're not ethical--

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:41.870
and people discover
that-- then it

00:38:41.870 --> 00:38:44.480
becomes like a wildfire
on the internet

00:38:44.480 --> 00:38:48.560
to say like this is the
unscrupulous way in which

00:38:48.560 --> 00:38:49.790
this brand is doing business.

00:38:49.790 --> 00:38:52.370
And that can cause them
to fail a lot faster.

00:38:52.370 --> 00:38:54.149
Can you talk about
that a little bit?

00:38:54.149 --> 00:38:54.940
LUCAS CONLEY: Yeah.

00:38:54.940 --> 00:38:56.480
Actually, Mark can
speak a little bit more

00:38:56.480 --> 00:38:57.860
on the client
side, but I can say

00:38:57.860 --> 00:39:01.460
that, right out of the gate,
we had an assumption when

00:39:01.460 --> 00:39:04.370
we published this book and
started doing the work that we

00:39:04.370 --> 00:39:06.920
were doing that the types of
brands that would approach us

00:39:06.920 --> 00:39:10.772
would be the longstanding
brands, the brands that were

00:39:10.772 --> 00:39:12.230
in trouble of going
out of business

00:39:12.230 --> 00:39:14.780
and wanted to
preserve their legacy.

00:39:14.780 --> 00:39:16.850
What we found is,
actually, the majority

00:39:16.850 --> 00:39:19.100
of the brands that approach
us are the younger brands,

00:39:19.100 --> 00:39:20.810
the newer brands.

00:39:20.810 --> 00:39:24.560
And sometimes brands that
are very popular, they've

00:39:24.560 --> 00:39:27.840
got some great product, but
haven't spent the time to say,

00:39:27.840 --> 00:39:28.700
what are we about?

00:39:28.700 --> 00:39:30.470
Like what do what do we do?

00:39:30.470 --> 00:39:33.350
You can actually share, if you
want to share that tech story.

00:39:33.350 --> 00:39:35.470
That's probably
relevant to this.

00:39:35.470 --> 00:39:37.470
MARK MILLER: At the front
of the first chapter?

00:39:37.470 --> 00:39:38.210
Is that what you're thinking of?

00:39:38.210 --> 00:39:40.250
LUCAS CONLEY: I'm thinking
about the consulting

00:39:40.250 --> 00:39:41.330
prior to the book.

00:39:41.330 --> 00:39:43.538
MARK MILLER: So there's a
company that may or may not

00:39:43.538 --> 00:39:47.990
be in this neck of the woods
that likely works in the tech

00:39:47.990 --> 00:39:50.960
space that came with an
interesting proposition, which

00:39:50.960 --> 00:39:54.890
was they could tell us what
they were building that night,

00:39:54.890 --> 00:39:56.960
but they had a hard time
thinking about what they

00:39:56.960 --> 00:39:58.217
were building in the future.

00:39:58.217 --> 00:40:00.050
And it became particularly
relevant for them

00:40:00.050 --> 00:40:03.230
because as they were looking to
mature as an organization, had

00:40:03.230 --> 00:40:05.660
investors who were asking
hard questions of them, which

00:40:05.660 --> 00:40:08.240
is in a sea of companies
that are popping up overnight

00:40:08.240 --> 00:40:11.870
with interesting things,
was yours worth backing?

00:40:11.870 --> 00:40:13.970
And their honest
assessment of it

00:40:13.970 --> 00:40:17.829
was they did not know how
to answer that question.

00:40:17.829 --> 00:40:19.370
And that became
incredibly important.

00:40:19.370 --> 00:40:21.079
And that's fairly
common, which is

00:40:21.079 --> 00:40:23.370
we see plenty of people who
walk in the agency who say,

00:40:23.370 --> 00:40:24.890
my goal is they're going
to start a company,

00:40:24.890 --> 00:40:27.120
sell it for a billion
dollars as fast as I can,

00:40:27.120 --> 00:40:28.340
and then I'm done.

00:40:28.340 --> 00:40:31.220
And our endeavor
is actually to say,

00:40:31.220 --> 00:40:32.810
our thinking is not
for those people.

00:40:32.810 --> 00:40:34.970
Our thinking is
not for everyone.

00:40:34.970 --> 00:40:36.380
Technology is changing.

00:40:36.380 --> 00:40:37.922
Things are moving
at a fast pace.

00:40:37.922 --> 00:40:39.380
But it's not
permission to not have

00:40:39.380 --> 00:40:41.900
a long-term ambition or a goal.

00:40:41.900 --> 00:40:44.674
So the ones who define their
businesses only by the hardware

00:40:44.674 --> 00:40:47.090
are the ones who are most
likely to be copied and imitated

00:40:47.090 --> 00:40:48.290
quickly at a lower price.

00:40:48.290 --> 00:40:50.190
And the ones who say,
the hardware is simply

00:40:50.190 --> 00:40:52.910
a manifestation of a
larger idea are the ones

00:40:52.910 --> 00:40:55.720
who have an opportunity to last
for a longer period of time.

00:40:55.720 --> 00:40:57.470
The other story that
I'll add very quickly

00:40:57.470 --> 00:40:59.053
is at the start of
our first chapter--

00:40:59.053 --> 00:41:01.820
the start of all our chapters,
we rip stories out of culture.

00:41:01.820 --> 00:41:03.830
So the vast majority of
stories that we covered

00:41:03.830 --> 00:41:05.390
are based on primary
research, but at the front

00:41:05.390 --> 00:41:07.250
of every chapter you
find what was supposed

00:41:07.250 --> 00:41:09.800
to be an iconic leader
that everyone in the world

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:12.410
would agree is making the
kind of positive change

00:41:12.410 --> 00:41:14.384
that it eases you
into a chapter.

00:41:14.384 --> 00:41:15.800
So right at the
start of chapter 1

00:41:15.800 --> 00:41:17.780
is Mark Zuckerberg
from Facebook.

00:41:17.780 --> 00:41:19.680
And we wrote about
him before, of course,

00:41:19.680 --> 00:41:24.114
the questions came out
about transparency and data.

00:41:24.114 --> 00:41:26.030
And so we've subsequently
been asked questions

00:41:26.030 --> 00:41:28.250
about the degree to which
we stand behind the story.

00:41:28.250 --> 00:41:30.290
And we have the same
answer and we feel strongly

00:41:30.290 --> 00:41:32.810
about it, which is we
didn't write the history

00:41:32.810 --> 00:41:36.164
book on brands that forevermore
are doing exceptional things.

00:41:36.164 --> 00:41:38.330
We covered a moment in time
where leaders and brands

00:41:38.330 --> 00:41:40.774
were doing exemplary work.

00:41:40.774 --> 00:41:42.440
And if they want to
be in the next book,

00:41:42.440 --> 00:41:44.630
they would continue to hold
fast to the values that

00:41:44.630 --> 00:41:45.680
got them there.

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:47.660
And if they abandon
them, they likely

00:41:47.660 --> 00:41:48.940
wouldn't be in the next book.

00:41:48.940 --> 00:41:51.230
So we actually found it not--

00:41:51.230 --> 00:41:52.970
it was a fascinating
thing, which

00:41:52.970 --> 00:41:55.700
is it forced us and the readers
of the book and the press

00:41:55.700 --> 00:41:58.340
as well to confront the
reality that we weren't talking

00:41:58.340 --> 00:42:01.190
about people who should be
famous for what they once did.

00:42:01.190 --> 00:42:02.720
We're talking about
people who live

00:42:02.720 --> 00:42:04.760
by their words every
single day and helped

00:42:04.760 --> 00:42:06.040
to write history every day.

00:42:09.440 --> 00:42:10.300
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:42:10.300 --> 00:42:11.591
LUCAS CONLEY: Yeah, absolutely.

00:42:14.715 --> 00:42:16.340
AUDIENCE: In a similar
vein, you talked

00:42:16.340 --> 00:42:18.290
about Blockbuster
and RadioShack,

00:42:18.290 --> 00:42:21.795
who their business
model kind of went away.

00:42:21.795 --> 00:42:23.420
But there's a lot of
theories about how

00:42:23.420 --> 00:42:25.370
they could have pivoted
or recontextualized

00:42:25.370 --> 00:42:27.000
to still exist.

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.300
So are they examples of
companies that kind of

00:42:29.300 --> 00:42:30.860
maintained their
legacy and values,

00:42:30.860 --> 00:42:33.627
while having to change what
they did pretty fundamentally?

00:42:33.627 --> 00:42:35.460
LUCAS CONLEY: It's
interesting you say that.

00:42:35.460 --> 00:42:38.210
The story that we also put in
the book at the very beginning

00:42:38.210 --> 00:42:39.280
is Kodak too.

00:42:39.280 --> 00:42:42.230
We kind of bunched those three
together as cautionary tales.

00:42:42.230 --> 00:42:44.660
And I love the Kodak
version as a cautionary tale

00:42:44.660 --> 00:42:46.715
because they actually
invented the digital camera

00:42:46.715 --> 00:42:49.130
back in like 1974.

00:42:49.130 --> 00:42:51.700
And somebody brought
it to an executive

00:42:51.700 --> 00:42:54.320
and the executive said this
would ruin our photo business.

00:42:54.320 --> 00:42:56.750
We have printing
booths everywhere.

00:42:56.750 --> 00:42:58.034
That's all our revenue.

00:42:58.034 --> 00:43:00.200
This is not something that
we want to put out there.

00:43:00.200 --> 00:43:02.570
So they buried the
invention, and ultimately it

00:43:02.570 --> 00:43:04.590
was their demise.

00:43:04.590 --> 00:43:08.390
So it's a fascinating
little case study.

00:43:08.390 --> 00:43:11.150
As far as brands that
have transitioned,

00:43:11.150 --> 00:43:13.430
what I do think
is interesting is

00:43:13.430 --> 00:43:15.779
some of the brands in the
book will come to us and say--

00:43:15.779 --> 00:43:17.320
The Honest Company
is a good example.

00:43:17.320 --> 00:43:19.340
They're right here,
right around the corner.

00:43:19.340 --> 00:43:21.920
They'll tell you we
build these products

00:43:21.920 --> 00:43:24.635
or we sell these
products, but tomorrow we

00:43:24.635 --> 00:43:26.510
could be selling something
entirely different

00:43:26.510 --> 00:43:29.960
because it's the values and
our mission aren't necessarily

00:43:29.960 --> 00:43:31.172
about the products.

00:43:31.172 --> 00:43:32.630
The Honest Company,
for example, is

00:43:32.630 --> 00:43:35.160
about a cleaner, greener world.

00:43:35.160 --> 00:43:37.390
They could be making
clothing next year.

00:43:37.390 --> 00:43:39.590
They would still stay
true to that principle.

00:43:39.590 --> 00:43:42.140
They would just be doing
that in a different industry.

00:43:42.140 --> 00:43:44.690
I've been surprised by how
many times we've heard that.

00:43:44.690 --> 00:43:47.126
But can you think
of examples or--

00:43:47.126 --> 00:43:49.250
MARK MILLER: Ritz-Carlton's
another reasonable one,

00:43:49.250 --> 00:43:51.009
which is in response
to the question,

00:43:51.009 --> 00:43:53.300
in a hundred years from now,
what do you hope persists?

00:43:53.300 --> 00:43:55.258
One of the founding
members was very reflective

00:43:55.258 --> 00:43:57.590
and he said, if the
hotels look the same

00:43:57.590 --> 00:43:59.824
and if people dress
the same, and if people

00:43:59.824 --> 00:44:01.490
act in exactly the
same way, then people

00:44:01.490 --> 00:44:04.190
fundamentally misunderstand
what this brand is all about.

00:44:04.190 --> 00:44:06.400
We're about ladies and
gentlemen treating people

00:44:06.400 --> 00:44:07.400
as ladies and gentlemen.

00:44:07.400 --> 00:44:08.900
We're about
graciousness and manners

00:44:08.900 --> 00:44:10.689
in a world that is
often without them.

00:44:10.689 --> 00:44:12.230
And to a degree,
we're about creating

00:44:12.230 --> 00:44:14.369
memories that last a lifetime.

00:44:14.369 --> 00:44:16.410
So it's not just about a
two or three night stay,

00:44:16.410 --> 00:44:19.940
it's about us a seven
memory stay, for example.

00:44:19.940 --> 00:44:23.810
And his point was we teach
culture and value every day,

00:44:23.810 --> 00:44:25.444
and that's why today
we have hotels,

00:44:25.444 --> 00:44:27.110
and tomorrow we're
going to have yachts,

00:44:27.110 --> 00:44:30.320
and beyond that the Ritz-Carlton
might manifest as something

00:44:30.320 --> 00:44:33.044
fundamentally different than
a conventional hotel company.

00:44:33.044 --> 00:44:34.460
They got an
interesting phone call

00:44:34.460 --> 00:44:38.690
from a documentarian, a group
that was making a documentary.

00:44:38.690 --> 00:44:40.445
And they said, we're
going to cover Airbnb

00:44:40.445 --> 00:44:43.130
and we're going to cover
the Ritz-Carlton as examples

00:44:43.130 --> 00:44:47.180
of iconic, successful
hospitality spaces today.

00:44:47.180 --> 00:44:49.836
And their question
was, which hotels

00:44:49.836 --> 00:44:50.960
do you want us to document?

00:44:50.960 --> 00:44:54.470
And Ritz-Carlton said,
effectively, we don't care.

00:44:54.470 --> 00:44:55.842
And they said, what do you mean?

00:44:55.842 --> 00:44:57.550
Which of the hotels
you want to show off?

00:44:57.550 --> 00:44:59.990
And they said, any of
them and none of them

00:44:59.990 --> 00:45:01.970
because what defines
us are not the walls.

00:45:01.970 --> 00:45:03.050
We'll tell you the
people that we'd

00:45:03.050 --> 00:45:05.050
like you to document
because we think the people

00:45:05.050 --> 00:45:07.790
and the style of service
is the thing that lives on.

00:45:07.790 --> 00:45:10.530
And it took the media
company a while to digest it,

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:12.030
but when they
understood, they said,

00:45:12.030 --> 00:45:13.580
yeah, I guess that's
what makes you

00:45:13.580 --> 00:45:15.100
and Airbnb
fundamentally different.

00:45:15.100 --> 00:45:17.120
One's about the
spaces you occupy,

00:45:17.120 --> 00:45:19.000
and one's about the
interactions you have,

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:19.958
no matter where you go.

00:45:19.958 --> 00:45:21.380
And they said,
yes, that's what we

00:45:21.380 --> 00:45:25.100
hope lives for 100 years,
those human interactions.

00:45:25.100 --> 00:45:28.230
So over time, we'll look
to plus those stories.

00:45:28.230 --> 00:45:30.990
But I think Honest
is one in the making.

00:45:30.990 --> 00:45:33.950
I think Ritz is a brand
that's more than 30 years old.

00:45:33.950 --> 00:45:36.050
It's probably not a bad one.

00:45:36.050 --> 00:45:40.250
And it'd be curious to see
what happens with brands

00:45:40.250 --> 00:45:42.624
like Bluebird over time.

00:45:42.624 --> 00:45:43.790
They're a fascinating story.

00:45:43.790 --> 00:45:46.280
They refuse to
knock down the walls

00:45:46.280 --> 00:45:48.740
and make it a venue for
thousands of people.

00:45:48.740 --> 00:45:52.360
They say that if the performers
can't see the audience,

00:45:52.360 --> 00:45:53.515
the experience dies.

00:45:53.515 --> 00:45:54.890
And yet, they're
looking for ways

00:45:54.890 --> 00:45:57.056
to transport that experience
all over the world that

00:45:57.056 --> 00:45:58.817
doesn't violate their
culture and values.

00:45:58.817 --> 00:45:59.900
So it'll be a curious one.

00:46:05.330 --> 00:46:08.640
AUDIENCE: Question about
legacy when it comes to--

00:46:08.640 --> 00:46:10.850
industry is making
significant shifts.

00:46:10.850 --> 00:46:12.500
So like you guys
are from Team One.

00:46:12.500 --> 00:46:14.150
Automotive industry
is working to be

00:46:14.150 --> 00:46:17.000
like more mobility-focused
instead of selling cars.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:20.590
And like that's a
hard right, right?

00:46:20.590 --> 00:46:22.830
That's not like, oh,
let's think about this.

00:46:22.830 --> 00:46:25.410
They're trying to do
it really quickly.

00:46:25.410 --> 00:46:27.050
What's your guys'
take on legacy when

00:46:27.050 --> 00:46:29.960
there's companies that are
trying to take on things that

00:46:29.960 --> 00:46:31.970
might be outside of their zone?

00:46:35.061 --> 00:46:37.310
MARK MILLER: I can speak to
automotive directly, which

00:46:37.310 --> 00:46:42.350
is that world is changing so
dramatically that I believe

00:46:42.350 --> 00:46:43.790
if you sat down
with Akio Toyoda,

00:46:43.790 --> 00:46:47.720
he would tell you mobility
isn't a made up idea.

00:46:47.720 --> 00:46:50.310
That he would say mobility
was always a part of the DNA.

00:46:50.310 --> 00:46:52.940
Maybe it was not at
the top of the pyramid.

00:46:52.940 --> 00:46:54.984
Maybe it wasn't always
discussed and revealed.

00:46:54.984 --> 00:46:56.900
But he would tell you
the way they move people

00:46:56.900 --> 00:46:58.640
through the world, including
how they move people

00:46:58.640 --> 00:47:00.389
through a dealership,
how they move people

00:47:00.389 --> 00:47:03.320
through an online experience,
how they move people from home

00:47:03.320 --> 00:47:05.254
to work and beyond,
he would tell you

00:47:05.254 --> 00:47:06.920
it's a part of the
truth of the company.

00:47:06.920 --> 00:47:09.378
One of the supporters of our
book that we're quite proud of

00:47:09.378 --> 00:47:10.500
is Simon Sinek.

00:47:10.500 --> 00:47:12.895
And when Simon got involved
he was skeptical at first.

00:47:12.895 --> 00:47:15.020
He said, I'm sure you're
talking to a lot of people

00:47:15.020 --> 00:47:17.210
who are telling you fairy tales
and fantasies about what they

00:47:17.210 --> 00:47:19.340
wish they would become,
but don't represent

00:47:19.340 --> 00:47:20.540
the truth of what they are.

00:47:20.540 --> 00:47:22.289
And once we started
dissecting the stories

00:47:22.289 --> 00:47:26.570
and going through them, he
became a fan, particularly

00:47:26.570 --> 00:47:28.820
of the Fast Company's story.

00:47:28.820 --> 00:47:31.100
And I think he particularly
liked the Taylor story.

00:47:31.100 --> 00:47:33.650
But he really challenged
us, as you're appropriately

00:47:33.650 --> 00:47:36.020
doing, which is to
say, are you guys

00:47:36.020 --> 00:47:39.100
just showing the shiniest pieces
that companies want you to see?

00:47:39.100 --> 00:47:41.730
Or are these real
elements of the brand?

00:47:41.730 --> 00:47:43.160
So for automotive,
specifically, I

00:47:43.160 --> 00:47:46.850
think Toyota has some truth
in the notion of mobility.

00:47:46.850 --> 00:47:48.980
And what they look
like tomorrow better

00:47:48.980 --> 00:47:52.190
be fundamentally different
than today because otherwise

00:47:52.190 --> 00:47:53.450
they'll be dead and gone.

00:47:53.450 --> 00:47:54.640
AUDIENCE: Yeah, totally.

00:47:54.640 --> 00:47:57.015
I look at Mark Fields and what
they were doing with Ford,

00:47:57.015 --> 00:47:59.672
and it's like the Ford
past totally tanked, right?

00:47:59.672 --> 00:48:01.880
It's like how are you going
to do this the right way?

00:48:01.880 --> 00:48:04.810
And it's a big change.

00:48:04.810 --> 00:48:07.115
So you're right about
the DNA of Toyota always

00:48:07.115 --> 00:48:09.320
being about mobility,
but it's like how do you

00:48:09.320 --> 00:48:12.030
do it the right way and how do
you buy yourself enough time?

00:48:12.030 --> 00:48:13.959
Which is another
key piece of it.

00:48:13.959 --> 00:48:15.500
When you were talking
about switching

00:48:15.500 --> 00:48:17.370
from going from selling
cars or whatever

00:48:17.370 --> 00:48:19.940
it may be to whatever shift
you're doing as a company,

00:48:19.940 --> 00:48:22.562
how much of a period of
time do you need to change--

00:48:22.562 --> 00:48:24.020
even if it is part
of your legacy--

00:48:24.020 --> 00:48:26.360
change the dynamics
of your business?

00:48:26.360 --> 00:48:27.107
I'll shut up now.

00:48:27.107 --> 00:48:29.690
MARK MILLER: We write a piece
in the book-- right at the end--

00:48:29.690 --> 00:48:32.420
that talks about the
old measurement system

00:48:32.420 --> 00:48:34.850
was a simple evaluation
of assets and liabilities.

00:48:34.850 --> 00:48:37.820
So in a quarter, in a year, what
are the things that hold value?

00:48:37.820 --> 00:48:39.630
What are the things
that are losing value?

00:48:39.630 --> 00:48:42.920
And we worked with a semiotician
in London and built a model,

00:48:42.920 --> 00:48:45.072
which is concurrently
looking at latent value--

00:48:45.072 --> 00:48:46.530
those things that
still have value,

00:48:46.530 --> 00:48:48.785
but if you don't evolve
it, it becomes useless--

00:48:48.785 --> 00:48:50.410
and concurrently,
looking at the things

00:48:50.410 --> 00:48:51.530
that you change in real time.

00:48:51.530 --> 00:48:53.300
Because if you're not looking
ahead and creating things that

00:48:53.300 --> 00:48:54.920
don't exist, you're
going to find out

00:48:54.920 --> 00:48:58.160
that your Lexus is
unseated by Tesla,

00:48:58.160 --> 00:49:00.980
and Blockbuster's unseated
by Netflix because they never

00:49:00.980 --> 00:49:03.050
bother to pay attention,
and Ritz-Carlton

00:49:03.050 --> 00:49:05.060
could be unseated by
Airbnb because they were

00:49:05.060 --> 00:49:06.830
late to the timeshare game.

00:49:06.830 --> 00:49:09.650
So we do think it's
a fundamental shift.

00:49:09.650 --> 00:49:14.030
On the one hand, the idea
that repeat the past.

00:49:14.030 --> 00:49:16.130
If I just do that, I can't fail.

00:49:16.130 --> 00:49:17.450
Many understand that.

00:49:17.450 --> 00:49:19.100
Even if it fails,
who could say that I

00:49:19.100 --> 00:49:20.990
was wrong for doing
what once worked?

00:49:20.990 --> 00:49:24.080
Equally, we see the ones
who say, screw the past.

00:49:24.080 --> 00:49:25.490
The past was in the past.

00:49:25.490 --> 00:49:28.320
I'm here for my three year
tenure as a CMO or CEO.

00:49:28.320 --> 00:49:29.320
It's a whole new future.

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:31.880
I'm going to make my mark,
build my resume, and move on.

00:49:31.880 --> 00:49:34.100
The hardest thing is to
actually reconcile the two.

00:49:34.100 --> 00:49:36.440
What are the pieces of the
past worth hanging on to?

00:49:36.440 --> 00:49:38.106
And what are those
elements of modernity

00:49:38.106 --> 00:49:40.350
that we better add or
we're going to fail?

00:49:40.350 --> 00:49:44.450
So I think we have good examples
of brands in the making.

00:49:44.450 --> 00:49:47.827
And I think this is going to
be a constant work in progress.

00:49:47.827 --> 00:49:48.619
LUCAS CONLEY: Yeah.

00:49:48.619 --> 00:49:49.576
MARK MILLER: Thank you.

00:49:49.576 --> 00:49:50.870
AUDIENCE: Appreciate your time.

00:49:50.870 --> 00:49:53.620
[APPLAUSE]

